00:47.474 --> 00:49.772
<i>My dad always told me stories about her-</i>

00:50.878 --> 00:54.439
<i>How she was this great
oceanographer.</i>

00:55.449 --> 00:57.917
<i>Stories about
the baby they had...</i>

00:57.985 --> 01:01.079
<i>and how my mom
just had to name her... Nim.</i>

01:01.155 --> 01:03.350
<i>She invented that name.</i>

01:03.424 --> 01:05.949
<i>At least, that's how my dad
tells the story.</i>

01:08.028 --> 01:12.397
<i>That's all my mother is to me now-
just these stories.</i>

01:13.701 --> 01:17.569
<i>But they're really
some amazing stories.</i>

01:19.373 --> 01:24.834
<i>Like the one he calls
"The Oceanographer and the Great Blue Whale."</i>

01:27.314 --> 01:32.047
<i>Once upon a time, the oceanographer
went out on the wide-open sea...</i>

01:32.119 --> 01:36.647
<i>to find out what was in the stomach
of the great blue whale.</i>

01:39.193 --> 01:41.957
<i>As my mother was staring into
the mouth of the whale...</i>

01:42.029 --> 01:44.998
<i>a mysterious ship
came out of nowhere.</i>

01:46.734 --> 01:49.635
<i>It was called
The Buccaneer Ship.</i>

01:50.838 --> 01:53.932
<i>It got much too close,
and it frightened the whale.</i>

01:54.008 --> 01:58.707
<i>And the oceanographer
was swallowed and taken by the sea.</i>

02:01.782 --> 02:05.980
<i>Dad felt that we should sail the ocean
and look for that blue whale-</i>

02:06.053 --> 02:09.113
<i>that, someday, that whale
would bring her back to us.</i>

02:10.457 --> 02:13.392
<i>I think he just missed her.</i>

02:13.460 --> 02:15.394
<i>We both did.</i>

02:17.398 --> 02:21.732
<i>By my fourth birthday,
we had sailed around the globe... twice-</i>

02:21.802 --> 02:24.930
<i>From the Cape of Good Hope
to the tip of Ratagonia...</i>

02:25.005 --> 02:27.439
<i>from Singapore
to the Cook Islands.</i>

02:28.942 --> 02:32.275
<i>Then one day, we found it-</i>

02:33.480 --> 02:35.539
<i>our home.</i>

02:41.121 --> 02:43.055
<i>This is my island.</i>

02:45.059 --> 02:47.721
<i>Not a bad place to grow up, huh?</i>

02:47.795 --> 02:50.491
<i>See, I don't have to
go to school.</i>

02:50.564 --> 02:52.691
<i>- I'm home-schooled.
- Hey, Selkie!</i>

02:52.766 --> 02:54.324
Watch out! Move it!

02:54.401 --> 02:57.029
<i>Or, technically, island-schooled.</i>

02:57.104 --> 03:00.335
Sorry!

03:00.407 --> 03:04.400
<i>- Everything I know about the world
I learned from my friends.</i>

03:04.478 --> 03:06.537
Galileo!

03:06.613 --> 03:08.547
<i>Like, do you know
that two objects...</i>

03:08.615 --> 03:12.244
<i>no matter how big they are,
will fall at exactly the same speed?</i>

03:12.319 --> 03:16.085
<i>Galileo proved it.
He's my pelican.</i>

03:17.925 --> 03:20.917
<i>Selkie, my sea lion,
taught me how to swim.</i>

03:20.994 --> 03:24.555
<i>So I returned the favor by teaching her soccer.</i>

03:24.631 --> 03:26.963
<i>She's an excellent midfielder.</i>

03:28.802 --> 03:32.932
<i>Oh, and I'll bet you didn't know that
sea turtles and certain species oflizards...</i>

03:33.006 --> 03:35.201
<i>really get on each other's nerves.</i>

03:39.680 --> 03:41.807
<i>Anything else
I need to know about the world...</i>

03:41.882 --> 03:45.045
<i>I just open one of the books
my dad brought for me.</i>

03:45.119 --> 03:49.453
<i>With a little imagination, I can go anywhere.</i>

03:54.862 --> 03:57.763
<i>All in all, not a bad life.</i>

03:57.831 --> 04:01.267
<i>For dinner, I throw together
some vegetables from our garden.</i>

04:01.335 --> 04:05.829
<i>And for a little extra flavor,
I toss in some freshly dug-up mealworms.</i>

04:05.906 --> 04:08.397
<i>Mmm. My dad's favorite.</i>

04:08.475 --> 04:11.410
Incredible day, Nim.
A new species, I think.

04:11.478 --> 04:13.844
Well, if it's new, remember
what you're naming it.

04:13.914 --> 04:16.178
"Protozoa Nim."
I haven't forgotten.

04:16.250 --> 04:19.651
<i>See, my dad's a marine biologist.</i>

04:19.720 --> 04:22.814
<i>He's obsessed with nanoplankton,
the tiniest little particles in the ocean.</i>

04:22.890 --> 04:26.792
<i>They're not really my thing,
but to each his own, right?</i>

04:26.860 --> 04:30.921
Did you know there are millions
of picoplankton in a milliliter of water?

04:30.998 --> 04:33.694
Protozoa Nim could be here right now.

04:34.768 --> 04:37.293
What? Wha-

04:37.371 --> 04:40.431
- Hey, Lizard!
- He's not "Lizard." His name is Fred.

04:43.377 --> 04:47.313
<i>For a guy who loves nature,
you'd think he'd be more into animals.</i>

04:47.381 --> 04:51.681
<i>When they have more than one cell,
Jack sort of loses interest.</i>

04:51.752 --> 04:57.213
<i>Scientists write to him from all over the world
with questions about all sorts of things.</i>

04:57.291 --> 04:59.816
<i>He even writes articles sometimes...</i>

04:59.893 --> 05:02.953
<i>like this great one
for National Geographic.</i>

05:06.800 --> 05:09.894
- What's the reading?
- Thirty-seven knots!

05:11.872 --> 05:14.898
<i>Hey, I'm not saying a scientist's
life is for everyone...</i>

05:14.975 --> 05:17.375
<i>but it is the life for us.</i>

05:20.447 --> 05:24.213
<i>Every few months, the supply ship comes,
bringing us things that we need.</i>

05:24.284 --> 05:27.583
<i>New books and paper,
nails and cloth-</i>

05:27.654 --> 05:30.350
<i>All the things we can't
make for ourselves.</i>

05:32.926 --> 05:35.986
<i>We sail out
into the open water to meet it.</i>

05:37.731 --> 05:40.825
<i>No one, not even
the supply ship's captain...</i>

05:40.901 --> 05:45.235
<i>has ever seen how amazing
our little island really is.</i>

05:45.305 --> 05:49.537
We take care of our island, Nim,
our island's gonna take care of us.

05:50.811 --> 05:53.405
<i>And that's the way
we wanna keep it-</i>

05:53.480 --> 05:57.314
<i>our own perfect, secret world.</i>

06:00.053 --> 06:01.953
<i>- Are ya ready?
- I'm ready.</i>

06:05.158 --> 06:08.093
Ah, bounty.

06:08.161 --> 06:11.392
Look at this-
Heirloom tomato seeds.

06:11.465 --> 06:14.314
<i>Do you remember those freckled
ones we were reading about?</i>

06:14.315 --> 06:14.866
Check it out!

06:14.935 --> 06:18.371
<i>The new Alex Rover!
My Arabian Adventure.</i>

06:18.438 --> 06:20.599
What do you think happens
in Arabia?

06:20.674 --> 06:22.608
Wait until after dinner, Nim.

06:22.676 --> 06:25.144
No, I'm just gonna start it.

06:28.649 --> 06:31.914
<i>"It's been my curse my entire life.</i>

06:31.985 --> 06:36.479
<i>"I do not go looking for trouble,
but somehow it finds me.</i>

06:36.557 --> 06:38.889
<i>The question wasn't, am I going to die?</i>

06:38.959 --> 06:42.258
<i>The question was, how am I going to die?</i>

06:42.329 --> 06:47.232
<i>Will it be by my captors' guns,
or will it be death by thirst?</i>

06:48.569 --> 06:52.437
Must be the hero
of my own life story.

06:52.506 --> 06:55.703
Must be the hero
of my own life story.

06:55.776 --> 06:58.870
<i>Must be the hero
of my own life story.</i>

06:58.946 --> 07:01.779
Where are you taking me?

07:04.151 --> 07:08.815
A special hole, just for you,
Alex Rover.

07:09.957 --> 07:13.620
<i>Ever heard of the Pit of Spiders?</i>

07:16.196 --> 07:18.426
"Pit of Spiders," huh?

07:18.498 --> 07:21.023
Well, I guess that answers
the "how will I die" question.

07:46.426 --> 07:48.189
Aah!

07:52.466 --> 07:54.866
No, no, no, no! Wait, wait, wait, stop!

07:54.935 --> 07:57.335
Where're you going?

07:57.404 --> 08:01.864
Oh, death by thirst makes a late comeback.

08:09.416 --> 08:12.977
How did Alex Rover
get to be Alex Rover?

08:13.053 --> 08:16.511
- Well, let's see.
- Was he born with all that courage?

08:16.590 --> 08:18.581
"Was he born with all that courage?"

08:18.659 --> 08:20.627
Hmm.

08:20.694 --> 08:24.425
The thing about courage is...

08:24.498 --> 08:28.832
it's somethin' that we have to learn
and relearn our whole lives.

08:28.902 --> 08:31.370
You know, it's not just in you.

08:31.438 --> 08:34.839
It's in every choice we make,
each and every day.

08:38.645 --> 08:41.628
Where do you think Alex
Rover is at this very minute?

08:41.629 --> 08:42.842
Oh, well, I don't know.

08:42.916 --> 08:48.877
Maybe he's chained up in a sarcophagus
20,000 fathoms under the sea.

08:50.190 --> 08:52.385
Or in some pit of spiders...

08:52.459 --> 08:55.724
trapped without the antidote
for their poison.

08:55.796 --> 08:58.458
Yeah, pit of spiders.
I like that.

08:58.532 --> 09:01.558
Okay. Time to get some rest.

09:04.204 --> 09:06.195
Sleep tight, now, okay?

09:07.808 --> 09:10.368
And no dreaming about spiders.

09:43.009 --> 09:45.068
Spider! Spider!

09:47.247 --> 09:50.011
Get away from me.

09:51.918 --> 09:56.855
All right.
These all go back here.

09:56.923 --> 09:59.858
Straight. Right angles.

10:09.202 --> 10:11.966
Is-ls this the, uh,
Telegraph Hill Pharmacy?

10:12.038 --> 10:14.097
Yes, I need a delivery, please.

10:14.174 --> 10:16.108
Uh, Purell.

10:16.176 --> 10:18.701
Well, h-how many bottles do you have?

10:18.779 --> 10:20.838
Oh. Uh, very good.
All of them.

10:20.914 --> 10:22.848
Yeah. Send 'em all.

10:28.255 --> 10:30.189
<i>Uh, who is it?</i>

10:30.257 --> 10:33.192
<i>- Telegraph Hill Pharmacy.
- Uh, just leave it there, please.</i>

10:33.260 --> 10:35.228
Just leave it here?
In the rain?

10:35.295 --> 10:38.822
<i>Yeah, go ahead. I-I put it
on my MasterCard. I left you a very nice tip.</i>

10:38.899 --> 10:41.333
<i>- Uh, make sure you get it.
- Okay.</i>

10:56.249 --> 11:00.743
<i>Alexandra, it's Buffy, your favorite editor.</i>

11:00.821 --> 11:04.086
<i>I know you're there,
and I know you're not going to pick up.</i>

11:04.157 --> 11:06.091
<i>I just worry about you, darling...</i>

11:06.159 --> 11:08.889
<i>sitting at your computer,
living on a diet of only Progresso soup.</i>

11:10.030 --> 11:12.396
<i>- How can you eat that every day?
- Buffy.</i>

11:12.465 --> 11:14.558
<i>So, how is
the new Alex Rover coming?</i>

11:14.634 --> 11:17.467
<i>Wasn't I supposed to read
something two weeks ago?</i>

11:17.537 --> 11:20.131
<i>No pressure, no pressure,
no pressure.</i>

11:29.316 --> 11:33.116
<i>See, what you don't know about me
is that where there's an Alex Rover-</i>

11:33.186 --> 11:35.086
there's a way!

11:35.155 --> 11:39.091
I have a certain knack for getting out of
predicaments far worse than this one, you know.

11:39.159 --> 11:42.890
Eh. Excuse me?

11:42.963 --> 11:45.864
No, hold on. No. I'm supposed
to get outta this, you know.

11:45.932 --> 11:50.960
Alexandra!

11:52.439 --> 11:55.897
Why can't I get this?

11:55.976 --> 11:59.571
No pressure, no pressure,
no pressure.

12:01.214 --> 12:03.910
Volcanic sacrifice.
What was I thinking?

12:03.984 --> 12:06.475
<i>Volcano, volcano.</i>

12:07.554 --> 12:11.490
<i>"Living in the Shadow
of a Volcano. "Hmm.</i>

12:11.558 --> 12:14.425
Well, that's just crazy.
I mean, why would anyone do that?

12:30.644 --> 12:33.636
Oh, wow.

12:33.713 --> 12:35.977
Perfect.

12:55.168 --> 12:57.932
<i>- What you doin', Jack?
- Ah, there you are!</i>

12:58.004 --> 13:02.338
Current's shifted, Nim. Zander's Atoll
is gonna be just five feet underwater.

13:02.409 --> 13:04.843
<i>Zander's Atoll?
But it's almost dinner!</i>

13:04.911 --> 13:07.846
<i>Hey, we might not see algae
growth like this for years.</i>

13:07.914 --> 13:09.779
More plankton?

13:09.849 --> 13:11.942
This is the trip
we find Protozoa Nim.

13:12.018 --> 13:14.213
I swear it.
I can feel it in my bones.

13:14.287 --> 13:17.120
But Chicca's eggs are about to hatch.
I need to be here.

13:17.190 --> 13:21.251
No negotiating. I mean,
this is a once-in-a-lifetime experience.

13:21.328 --> 13:21.800
Come on!

13:21.801 --> 13:25.162
Yeah, you said that last week
about the southern borealis.

13:25.231 --> 13:29.691
- Two nights, Nim.
- No! Chicca only saved one last year, Jack.

13:29.769 --> 13:32.636
One little turtle. I want to stay.

13:32.706 --> 13:34.970
We can talk
on the satellite phone.

13:35.041 --> 13:37.805
Nim, please.

13:37.877 --> 13:40.345
I'm not a little girl anymore.

13:44.484 --> 13:47.044
You got so much of your mom in you,
you know that?

13:47.120 --> 13:49.554
<i>- That's a good thing, right?
- Yeah, good.</i>

13:49.622 --> 13:51.556
Sure.

13:51.624 --> 13:54.559
Unfortunately, I could never win a fight
with her either.

13:56.429 --> 13:59.193
<i>Okay, it's only four hours
till low tide.</i>

13:59.265 --> 14:02.860
Oh! Hey, could you grab
my collection jars and my wet suit?

14:02.936 --> 14:04.870
<i>I already packed them for you!</i>

14:04.938 --> 14:08.430
Any e-mails show up, tell 'em I'm on expedition.
I'll get to their questions on Thursday.

14:08.508 --> 14:10.442
Hey, Lizard, get off of that.

14:10.510 --> 14:12.239
<i>He's not "Lizard."
His name is Fred.</i>

14:12.312 --> 14:15.281
<i>Unless it's, like,
a ridiculously obvious e-mail.</i>

14:15.348 --> 14:18.681
- Then I can help 'em, right?
- I'd rather you just said Thursday.

14:18.752 --> 14:20.845
Nim, are you sure
you're okay with this?

14:20.920 --> 14:22.717
Come on.
You've left me alone before.

14:22.789 --> 14:24.916
Well, yeah. One night.
But never for two.

14:24.991 --> 14:29.394
Well, look, I've got Selkie and Fred
and Galileo and the new Alex Rover book.

14:29.462 --> 14:32.522
- I'll be excellent.
- All right, all right.

14:34.567 --> 14:37.968
- You just come back with Protozoa Nim!
- I will!

14:38.038 --> 14:41.132
I'll see ya Thursday!
Love you!

14:41.207 --> 14:43.471
Love you too!

14:43.543 --> 14:46.137
I'll radio you tonight!

14:46.212 --> 14:49.613
No parties while I'm gone!

14:51.451 --> 14:55.478
<i>#Baby, baby
please let me hold him #</i>

14:55.555 --> 15:00.049
<i>#I wanna make him stay up all night #</i>

15:00.126 --> 15:04.153
<i>#Sister, Sister
He's just a plaything #</i>

15:04.230 --> 15:07.893
<i># We wanna make him
stay up all night #</i>

15:07.967 --> 15:10.265
<i>#Here we go #</i>

15:17.877 --> 15:22.211
<i>#See him drink from a bottle #</i>

15:22.282 --> 15:23.909
<i>#See him eat from a plate ##</i>

15:25.518 --> 15:28.612
<i>Ooh, two new e-mails.
Aren't we popular?</i>

15:28.688 --> 15:30.417
<i>Hey, Freddie.</i>

15:30.490 --> 15:32.515
How's it goin'?

15:32.592 --> 15:36.892
"Dear Jack Rusoe, I need a bit of help
on my newest adventure.

15:36.963 --> 15:40.956
Might you be able to answer
a few questions for me? Alex Rover."

15:41.034 --> 15:42.934
Alex Rover?

15:43.002 --> 15:45.493
Alex Rover is writing to my dad?

15:45.572 --> 15:48.598
<i>Do you think it's the Alex Rover?</i>

15:51.544 --> 15:56.311
It's him! It's him! It's really him!

15:56.382 --> 16:01.843
Dear Alex Rover, I'm sure Jack would love
to help you with your newest adventure.

16:01.921 --> 16:06.290
He's a great fan of yours.
We both are.

16:06.359 --> 16:10.090
From... Nim.

16:19.105 --> 16:21.039
<i>"Dear Alex Rover...</i>

16:21.107 --> 16:24.634
<i>"I'm sure Jack would love to help you
with your newest adventure.</i>

16:24.711 --> 16:29.444
<i>"He'll be back on Thursday.
He's a great fan of yours. We both are.</i>

16:29.516 --> 16:31.711
From Nim."

16:31.784 --> 16:36.050
Nim. Hmm, what an unusual name.

16:38.358 --> 16:42.795
<i>Dear Nim, are you Jack's
research associate?</i>

16:42.862 --> 16:45.524
<i>Jack wrote of a volcano
where you live.</i>

16:45.598 --> 16:49.591
Are you familiar with it?
Sincerely, Alex Rover.

16:49.669 --> 16:51.603
Send.

16:52.839 --> 16:56.866
- What are you doing, Alexandra?
- Um, research.

16:56.943 --> 16:59.104
Go. Go. Go away.
Leave me alone.

16:59.179 --> 17:02.615
You don't mean that.
You love me.

17:02.682 --> 17:05.515
And what makes you so sure of that, huh?

17:06.653 --> 17:11.056
Because the whole world
loves Alex Rover.

17:11.124 --> 17:14.582
Really? I know.
"Translated into 21 different languages."

17:14.661 --> 17:17.289
No pressure, no pressure,
no pressure.

17:22.101 --> 17:24.092
You've been writing chapter eight
for three months now.

17:24.170 --> 17:29.437
So either sacrifice me to the damn volcano
or let me find my escape already.

17:29.509 --> 17:33.468
- Hey! It's time to finish the book.
- Shh!

17:33.546 --> 17:36.845
- I'm thinking.
- Yeah. You're thinking. You're thinking.

17:36.916 --> 17:41.410
That's the problem. You've gotta
get outta your head and into your body.

17:41.487 --> 17:44.888
Hey, that's it. Kinka.

17:44.958 --> 17:46.892
"Kinka"?

17:46.960 --> 17:48.894
Kinka!

17:50.063 --> 17:51.997
Kinka!

17:53.066 --> 17:55.967
Kinka!

18:02.909 --> 18:04.809
Yeah!

18:13.820 --> 18:15.913
<i>It was incredible, Jack.</i>

18:15.989 --> 18:19.322
<i>Chicca's babies were born
tonight, just like I said.</i>

18:19.392 --> 18:22.520
<i>- That's excellent.
- And the mole crabs were crazy hungry.</i>

18:22.595 --> 18:27.464
<i>It was so important that I stayed.
I saved all six turtles.</i>

18:27.533 --> 18:29.933
<i>Well, they're lucky you were there.
I'm proud of you, honey.</i>

18:30.003 --> 18:33.700
- How's Zander's Atoll?
- Oh, I wish you could see this, Nim. It's-

18:33.773 --> 18:37.174
I mean, it's more incredible
than the Milky Way.

18:37.243 --> 18:39.302
Next time
there's no negotiating, okay?

18:39.379 --> 18:42.143
Have you found
my nanoplankton yet?

18:42.215 --> 18:45.742
Mmm. I have a pretty good
feeling about it.

18:48.221 --> 18:51.452
Now, go to sleep, Nim. No more reading.
We'll talk in the morning.

18:51.524 --> 18:53.719
How did you know I was reading?

18:53.793 --> 18:56.489
Oh, I know you pretty well.

18:58.264 --> 19:01.995
Good night, Nim.
Sleep tight.

19:04.737 --> 19:09.071
It's just magnificent.

20:01.894 --> 20:04.226
No!

20:49.542 --> 20:53.308
Jack?
Daddy?

21:11.264 --> 21:13.198
<i>Oh, no.</i>

21:30.483 --> 21:34.044
Freddie!

22:05.818 --> 22:07.786
It's a mess in here, eh, Selk?

22:19.465 --> 22:23.663
No power. This rots.

22:47.426 --> 22:50.190
Jack?

22:51.364 --> 22:56.529
<i>Can you hear me?
Jack... Michael... Rusoe?</i>

22:57.537 --> 23:01.098
<i>Daddy, can you hear me?</i>

23:01.173 --> 23:03.869
<i>Jack?</i>

23:03.943 --> 23:06.571
<i>Come in, Daddy!</i>

23:09.582 --> 23:13.211
<i>Jack? Daddy?</i>

24:02.401 --> 24:04.528
<i>Protozoa Nim.</i>

24:05.705 --> 24:08.902
Leak. Leak is not good.

24:08.975 --> 24:11.466
Nobody likes a leak.

24:20.219 --> 24:23.052
<i>Oh.</i>

24:24.056 --> 24:25.990
Middle of nowhere.

24:27.994 --> 24:31.794
No mast. No satellite.

24:31.864 --> 24:34.594
Sinking ship.

24:37.703 --> 24:41.833
How do I get back to Nim?

24:55.588 --> 24:58.318
He's not even due back till tomorrow, right, Fred?

24:58.391 --> 25:00.689
Nothin' to worry about.

25:30.056 --> 25:33.219
Gotta get food. I gotta get strength.

25:33.292 --> 25:35.522
